In this paper, we propose a novel approach to image co-segmentation using deep metric learning. Co-segmentation, also known as simultaneous segmentation, is the task of segmenting multiple images simultaneously, where each image has its own object of interest and background. Existing methods for co-segmentation often rely on hand-crafted features or shallow neural networks, which may not capture complex relationships between images effectively.

In contrast, our proposed method leverages deep metric learning to learn a robust distance metric that captures the similarity between images in a high-dimensional feature space. We introduce a new loss function that combines both inter-image and intra-image information to optimize the learned distance metric. Our experiments demonstrate that the proposed method outperforms state-of-the-art co-segmentation methods on several benchmark datasets, including PASCAL VOC and Cityscapes. Moreover, we show that our method can handle various challenges such as occlusions, cluttered backgrounds, and large pose variations.

The main contributions of this work are:

* A novel deep metric learning framework for image co-segmentation;
* An effective loss function that integrates inter-image and intra-image information;
* Superior performance compared to existing methods on several benchmark datasets;
* Robustness to challenges such as occlusions, cluttered backgrounds, and large pose variations.

Our findings suggest that the proposed method has great potential for real-world applications in computer vision, robotics, and multimedia processing, where image co-segmentation plays an essential role.

In this paper, we propose a novel approach to fundus image segmentation using boundary and entropy-driven adversarial learning. We introduce a new convolutional neural network architecture that incorporates both boundary and entropy information to improve the accuracy of segmentation results. Our proposed method uses a combination of boundary detection and entropy measurement to guide the training process and optimize the network's performance.

Experiments conducted on several publicly available datasets demonstrate the superiority of our proposed method over existing state-of-the-art techniques. The inclusion of boundary and entropy information improves the accuracy and robustness of the model, especially in cases where the fundus images contain irregular or unclear boundaries. Additionally, we provide a thorough analysis of the effectiveness of different components of our proposed method, providing insights into the contributions of each component to the overall performance.

The main contributions of this work can be summarized as follows:

* A novel approach to fundus image segmentation using boundary and entropy-driven adversarial learning is proposed;
* A new CNN architecture that integrates both boundary and entropy information is introduced;
* Extensive experiments on public datasets show improved performance compared to existing methods;
* A detailed analysis of the contribution of each component of the proposed method is provided.

Our proposed method has important implications for real-world applications such as diabetic retinopathy diagnosis and treatment planning, where accurate fundus image segmentation is critical.
